Nippon Television Network Corp. (NTV) said Tuesday  its pre-tax earnings plunged 30 percent from a year earlier to 4.89 billion  yen (47 million dollars) in the year to March.
The broadcasting affiliate of the Yomiuri Shimbun, the top-selling  newspaper in Japan, said revenue fell 1.5 percent to 197 billion yen.
NTV forecast improved earnings of 5.5 billion yen for the coming year  despite a lower revenue projection of 194 billion yen.
In the year just ended, broadcasting revenue fell 0.6 percent to 119  billion yen, depressed by sales of television time which dropped 3.8 percent  to 44 billion yen. But spot advertising revenue was up 1.3 percent at 75  billion yen.
Revenue from program production declined 2.5 percent to 60 billion yen,  program sales fell 2.2 percent to eight billion yen and other revenue was down  4.8 percent at 10 billion yen, the company said.
